# IAM Fundamentals

## Why IAM Matters
AWS Identity and Access Management (IAM) controls who can access AWS resources and what actions they can perform. It is the foundation of cloud security.

## Core Components

### Users
- Represent individual identities
- Used for programmatic or console access
- Assigned permissions directly or through groups

### Groups
- Collection of users
- Simplifies permission management

### Roles
- Temporary access with defined permissions
- Used by AWS services (e.g., EC2) or federated identities
- No long-term credentials required

---

# Permissions and Policies

## Policies
- JSON documents defining allowed or denied actions
- Attached to users, groups, or roles

## Principle of Least Privilege
- Grant only the permissions required
- Reduce security risk and attack surface

